AB  - Biodiversity action plans outline targets to meet current declines in populations of threatened species. The creation or restoration of suitable habitat is fundamental to meeting these targets. Sites were identified for conservation management prescriptions using associative modelling techniques through the framework of a Geographical Information System (GIS) for three species of bird. An environmental model was developed from habitat survey data using multilevel modelling. A geostatistical indicator kriging model was developed from presence absence distribution records. Both models were combined following Bayesian decision rules to produce a refined data map layer of probability values of occurrence. Habitat suitability threshold values were assigned to these probability maps to identify those sites of high suitability. These sites were then overlaid to identify those that were shared by all three focal species. It is these sites that were finally identified as those to conserve using the existing management prescriptions of the Upper Thames Tributaries Environmentally Sensitive Area as a potential funding mechanism.
